@endnode

@node "set" "(set <varname> <value> [<varname2> <value2> ...])"

(set <varname> <value> [<varname2> <value2> ...])
   
Set the variable <varname> to the indicated value.  If <varname> does not
exist it will be created.  Set returns the value of the last assignment.

Note: All @{" variables " link "Data types"} are typeless, and any variable may be used wherever
a string could be used.  All variables are global.

The "set" statement can be used to convert a string to an integer value:

    (set <integer-var> (+ <string-var>))

Use the "@{" cat " link "cat"}" statement to do the reverse.

@endnode

@node "makedir" "(makedir <name> <parameters>)"

(makedir <name> <parameters>)

Creates a new directory.  Parameters:

    @{" prompt  " link "prompt"}  - tell the user what's going to happen.

    @{" help    " link "help"}  - text of help message.

    @{" infos   " link "infos"}  - create an icon for directory.

    @{" confirm " link "confirm"}  - if this option is present, user will be prompted, else the
                 directory will be created silently.
 
    @{" safe    " link "safe"}  - make directory even if in @{" PRETEND mode " link "Pretend mode"}.

@endnode

@node "copyfiles" "(copyfiles <parameters>)"

(copyfiles <parameters>)

Copies one or more files from the install disk to a target directory.
Each file will be displayed with a checkmark next to the name indicating if
the file should be copied or not.  Note that a write protected file is
considered "delete protected" as well.  Parameters:

    @{" prompt  " link "prompt"}  - tell the user what's going to happen.

    @{" help    " link "help"}  - text of help message.

    @{" source  " link "source"}  - name of source directory or file.

    @{" dest    " link "dest"}  - name of destination directory, which is created if it doesn't
                 exist. 
                 Note that both source and dest may be relative pathnames.

    @{" newname " link "newname"}  - if copying one file only, and file is to be renamed, this is
                 the new name.

    @{" choices " link "choices"}  - a list of files/directories to be copied (optional).

    @{" all     " link "all"}  - all files/directories in the source directory should be copied.

    @{" pattern " link "pattern"}  - indicates that files/directories from the source dir matching
                 a pattern should be copied.  The pattern should be no more
                 than 64 characters long.
                 Note that only one of "choices", "all" or "pattern" should be
                 used at any one time.

    @{" files   " link "files"}  - only copy files.  

    @{" infos   " link "infos"}  - switch to copy icons along with other files/directories.

    @{" fonts   " link "fonts"}  - switch to not display ".font" files, yet still copy any that
                 match a directory that is being copied.

   (@{" optional " link "optional"} <option> <option> ...) - dictates what will be considered a
                 failure on copying.
                 The first three options are mutually exclusive (they may not
                 be specified together).
                 "fail"       - installer aborts if could not copy (the default)
                 "nofail"     - installer continues if could not copy
                 "oknodelete" - aborts if can't copy, unless reason was
                                "delete protected"
                 The next two options may be used with any other "optional" 
                 options.
                 "force"      - unprotect destination
                 "askuser"    - ask user if the file should be unprotected (but
                                not in novice)
                 In the case of "askuser", the default for novice mode is an
                 answer of "no". Therefore, you may want to use "force" to make
                 the novice mode default answer appear to be "yes".

   (@{" delopts " link "delopts"} <option> <option> ...) - removes options set by "@{" optional " link "optional"}".

    @{" confirm " link "confirm"}  - if this option is present, user will be prompted to indicate
                 which files are to be copied, else the files will be copied
                 silently.

    @{" safe    " link "safe"}  - copy files even if in @{" PRETEND mode " link "Pretend mode"}.

@endnode

@node "copylib" "(copylib <parameters>)"

(copylib <parameters>)

Copies one file using version checking; i.e., it only overwrites an existing
file if the new file has a higher version/revision number.  "Copylib" will
create the destination directory as long as there is only one level missing.
For example, copying to a non-existent "DEVS:midi" would create the directory
"midi", but copying to "DEVS:midi/extra" where neither "midi" nor "extra" 
exists would fail.  Note that a write protected library file is considered 
"delete protected" as well.  Parameters:

    @{" prompt  " link "prompt"}  - tell the user what's going to happen.

    @{" help    " link "help"}  - text of help message.

    @{" source  " link "source"}  - name of source directory or file

    @{" dest    " link "dest"}  - name of destination directory
                 Note that both source and dest may be relative pathnames.

    @{" newname " link "newname"}  - if copying one file only, and file is to be renamed,
                 this is the new name

    @{" infos   " link "infos"}  - switch to copy icons along with other files
   
   (@{" optional" link "optional"} <option> <option> ...) - dictates what will be considered a
                                       failure on copying.
        The first three options are mutually exclusive (they may not be
            specified together).
            "fail"         - installer aborts if could not copy (the default)
            "nofail"       - installer continues if could not copy
            "oknodelete"   - aborts if can't copy, unless reason was
                             "delete protected"

        The next two options may be used with any other "optional" options.
            "force"     - unprotect destination
            "askuser"   - ask user if the file should be unprotected
                          (but not in novice)
            In the case of "askuser", the default for novice mode is an 
            answer of "no".  Therefore, you may want to use "force" to make
            the novice mode default answer appear to be "yes".

   (@{" delopts " link "delopts"} <option> <option> ...) - removes options set by "optional"

    @{" confirm " link "confirm"}  - user will be asked to confirm.  Note that an EXPERT user
                 will be able to overwrite a newer file with an older one.

    @{" safe    " link "safe"}  - copy the file even if in @{" PRETEND mode " link "Pretend mode"}.

@endnode

@node "startup" "(startup <appname> <parameters>)"

(startup <appname> <parameters>)

This command edits the "S:user-startup" file, which is executed by the 
user's startup-sequence (Installer will modify the user's startup- sequence
if needed, although in a friendly way).  The "command" parameter is used to
declare AmigaDOS command lines which will be executed.  The command lines
are grouped by application, using the supplied argument "appname".  If there
is already an entry in "S:user-startup" for that application, the new command
lines will completely replace the old.  The command lines for other
applications will not be affected.  Note: The prompt and help parameters for
the "startup" statement are only used by the confirmation display to edit 
"user-startup".  This only happens in EXPERT mode.  Parameters:


    @{" prompt  " link "prompt"}  - tell the user what's going to happen.
    
    @{" help    " link "help"}  - text of help message.

    @{" command " link "command"}  - used to declare an AmigaDOS command line to be
                 executed at system startup.

@endnode

@node "tooltype" "(tooltype <parameters>)"

(tooltype <parameters>)

Modify an icon's tool type.  Normally the new tool type values will be set
up in advance by various statements in the install language (i.e. the user
does not actually have to type in the tooltype values).  For example, you
could use an "@{" askchoice " link "askchoice"}" to ask the user what type of screen resolution
they want and then format the tooltype string based on their choice.
The "tooltype" operation merely asks for a confirmation before actually
writing.  Parameters:

    @{" prompt         " link "prompt"}  - tell the user what's going to happen.

    @{" help           " link "help"}  - text of help message.

    @{" dest           " link "dest"}  - the icon to be modified.

    @{" settooltype    " link "settooltype"}  - the tooltype name and value string.

    @{" setdefaulttool " link "setdefaulttool"}  - default tool for a project.

    @{" setstack       " link "setstack"}  - set size of stack.

    @{" noposition     " link "noposition"}  - reset to NOICONPOSITION.

    @{" swapcolors     " link "swapcolors"}  - swap first two planes of icon's image if OS rev less 
                        than v36.

    @{" confirm        " link "confirm"}  - if this option is present, the user will be asked for
                        confirmation, otherwise the modification proceeds
                        silently.

    @{" safe           " link "safe"}  - make changes even if in @{" PRETEND mode " link "Pretend mode"}.

@endnode

@node "textfile" "(textfile <parameters>)"

(textfile <parameters>)

Creates a text file from other textfiles or computed text strings.  This can
be used to create configuration files, AREXX programs or execute scripts.
Parameters:

    @{" prompt  " link "prompt"}  - tell the user what's going to happen.

    @{" help    " link "help"}  - text of help message. 

    @{" dest    " link "dest"}  - the name of the text file to be created.

    @{" append  " link "append"}  - a string to be appended to the new text file.

    @{" include " link "include"}  - a text file to be appended to the new text file.

    @{" confirm " link "confirm"}  - if this option is present, the user will be asked for
                 confirmation, otherwise the writing proceeds silently.

    @{" safe    " link "safe"}  - create file even if in @{" PRETEND mode " link "Pretend mode"}.

@endnode

@node "execute" "(execute <argument> ...)"

(execute <argument> ...)

Executes an AmigaDOS script with the arguments given.  NOTE: Does not ask
user for confirmation, however this can be added by using "@{" askchoice " link "askchoice"}" or
"@{" askbool " link "askbool"}". Parameters:

    @{" prompt  " link "prompt"}  - tell the user what's going to happen.

    @{" help    " link "help"}  - text of help message. 

    @{" confirm " link "confirm"}  - if this option is present, the user will be asked for
                  confirmation, otherwise the execute proceeds silently.

    @{" safe    " link "safe"}  - execute script even if in @{" PRETEND mode " link "Pretend mode"}.

Returns a result if executed under 2.0.  Returns 0 under 1.3.  See @{" NOTES " link "notes" 27} for
workarounds under 1.3.

@endnode

@node "run" "(run <argument> ...)"

(run <argument> ...)

Executes a compiled program with the arguments given.  NOTE: Does not ask
user for confirmation, however this can be added by using "@{" askchoice " link "askchoice"}" or
"@{" askbool " link "askbool"}". Parameters:

    @{" prompt  " link "prompt"}  - tell the user what's going to happen.

    @{" help    " link "help"}  - text of help message. 

    @{" confirm " link "confirm"}  - if this option is present, the user will be asked for
                 confirmation, otherwise the run proceeds silently.

    @{" safe    " link "safe"}  - run program even if in @{" PRETEND mode " link "Pretend mode"}.

Returns a result if executed under 2.0.  Returns 0 under 1.3.  See @{" NOTES " link "notes" 27} for
workarounds under 1.3.

@endnode

@node "rexx" "(rexx <argument> ...)"

(rexx <argument> ...)

Executes an ARexx script with the arguments given.  NOTE: Does not ask user
for confirmation, however this can be added by using "@{" askchoice " link "askchoice"}" or 
"@{" askbool " link "askbool"}". If the ARexx server is not active, an error will be generated.
Parameters:

    @{" prompt  " link "prompt"}  - tell the user what's going to happen.

    @{" help    " link "help"}  - text of help message. 

    @{" confirm " link "confirm"}  - if this option is present, the user will be asked for
                 confirmation, otherwise the rexx script proceeds silently.

    @{" safe    " link "safe"}  - execute script even if in @{" PRETEND mode " link "Pretend mode"}.

@endnode

@node "makeassign" "(makeassign <assign> [<path>] (parameters))"

(makeassign <assign> [<path>] (parameters))

Assigns 'assign' to 'path'.  If 'path' is not specified, the assignment is
cleared.  Parameters:

    @{" safe    " link "safe"}  - assign even if in @{" PRETEND mode " link "Pretend mode"}.

Note: assign must be supplied without a colon; i.e. "ENV" not "ENV:".

@endnode

@node "rename" "(rename <oldname> <newname> <parameters>)"

(rename <oldname> <newname> <parameters>)

Renames a file or directory.  If the "@{" disk " link "disk"}" parameter is given, then this
command relabels the disk named oldname to newname.  When relabeling a disk,
ONLY include a colon in the oldname.  Returns 1 if the rename was successful,
0 if it failed.  Parameters:

    @{" prompt  " link "prompt"}  - tell the user what's going to happen.

    @{" help    " link "help"}  - text of help message. 

    @{" confirm " link "confirm"}  - if this option is present, the user will be asked for
                 confirmation, otherwise the rename proceeds silently.

    @{" disk    " link "disk"}  - switch to get rename to relabel a disk.

    @{" safe    " link "safe"}  - rename even if in @{" PRETEND mode " link "Pretend mode"}.

@endnode

@node "delete" "(delete <file> <parameters>)" 

(delete <file> <parameters>)

Delete a file.  Note that a write protected file is considered "delete
protected" as well.  Parameters:

    @{" prompt  " link "prompt"}  - tell the user what's going to happen.

    @{" help    " link "help"}  - text of help message. 

    @{" confirm " link "confirm"}  - if this option is present, the user will be asked for
                 confirmation, otherwise the delete proceeds silently.

   (@{" optional " link "optional"} <option> <option> ...) - should deletions be forced.
           options:
               "force"     - unprotect destination
               "askuser"   - ask user if the file should be unprotected
                             (but not in novice)
               In the case of "askuser", the default for novice mode is an
               answer of "no".  Therefore, you may want to use "force" to make
               the novice mode default answer appear to be "yes".

   (@{" delopts " link "delopts"} <option> <option> ...) - removes options set by "optional"

    @{" safe    " link "safe"}  - delete even if in @{" PRETEND mode " link "Pretend mode"}.

@endnode

@node "protect" "(protect <file> [<string of flags to change>] [<decimal mask>] <parameters>)"

(protect <file> [<string of flags to change>] [<decimal mask>] <parameters>)

Either gets the protection status of a file (if a second argument is not
given), or sets it.  Two methods exist for setting the status: string
(e.g. "+r -w +e -d") or numeric (e.g. 5).  The string method allows the
changing of any of the flags individually, while numeric writes to all flags
at once (possibly changing bits unintendedly).  The bits in the binary
representation of the decimal mask correspond to the flags in the following
manner:

8 7 6 5 4 3 2 1  <- Bit number

h s p a r w e d  <- corresponding protection flag

^ ^ ^ ^ ^ ^ ^ ^
| | | | | | | |
| | | | | | | +- \\
| | | | | | +--- | 0 = flag set
| | | | | +----- | 1 = flag clear
| | | | +------- /
| | | | 
| | | |
| | | +--------- \\
| | +----------- | 0 = flag clear
| +------------- | 1 = flag set
+--------------- /

Note that the meaning of the bits in the numeric value follows the DOS
convention that a 1 in the high four bits (flags "hspa") indicates that the
flag is set, while a 1 in the lower four bits (flags "rwed") indicates that
the flag is cleared.

When setting bits, "protect" returns 1 if the attempt succeeded, else it
returns a 0.  Getting the bits returns either the numeric value of the
protection status (see interpretation, above) or -1 upon failure.
Parameters:

    @{" safe    " link "safe"}  - change protection even if in @{" PRETEND mode " link "Pretend mode"}.

@endnode

@node "abort" "(abort <message> <message> ...)"

(abort <message> <message> ...)

Exits the installation procedure with the given messages and then processes
the @{" onerror " link "onerror"} statements (if any).

@endnode

@node "exit" "(exit <string> <string> ... (quiet))"

(exit <string> <string> ... (quiet))

This causes normal termination of a script.  If strings are provided, they
are displayed.  The "done with installation" message is then displayed.
The "@{" onerror " link "onerror"}" statements are not executed.  If (quiet) is specified, the
final report display is skipped.

@endnode

@node "complete" "(complete <number>)"

(complete <number>)

This statement is used to inform the user how complete the installation is.
The number (which must be between 0 and 100) will be printed in the title
bar of the installer window with a '%' sign.

@endnode

@node "message" "(message <string> <string> ...)"

(message <string> <string> ...)

This statement displays a message to the user in a window, along with
Proceed, Abort and optional Help buttons.  Note that messages are not
printed when running at user level 0 (novice).  Parameters:

    @{" help    " link "help"}  - optional help text

@endnode

@node "working" "(working <string> <string> ...)"

(working <string> <string> ...)

The strings will be concatenated to form a message which will appear below a
standard line that reads "Working on Installation".  Useful if you are doing
a long operation other than file copying (which has its own @{" status display " link "nogauge"}).

@endnode

@node "welcome" "(welcome <string> <string> ...)"

(welcome <string> <string> ...)

Installer looks for the occurrence of this statement in a script file during
compilation.  If it does not exist (as is the case for older scripts) the
"Welcome to the <@{" APPNAME " link "APPNAME"}> App installation utility" display is presented to
the user as soon as compilation has finished. If this statement is present,
Installer will not put up the "Welcome..." display until the (welcome)
statement is reached.  This allows for the execution of code before the first
displays come up.  Note that the state of the "@{" @user-level " link "user-level"}" and "@{" @pretend " link "pretend_var"}"
variables will be based on the initial defaults including any modification by
tooltypes.  The string arguments are prepended to the standard help text for
whichever of the two initial displays appears first.

@endnode

@node "Control Statements" "Control Statements"
   4.3  Control Statements

NOTE: Strings can be used as the result of a test expression.  An empty
string is considered a FALSE value, all others are considered TRUE.

                     @{" foreach    " link "foreach"}
                     @{" if         " link "if"}
                     @{" onerror    " link "onerror"}
                     @{" select     " link "select"}      
                     @{" trap       " link "trap"}   
                     @{" until      " link "until"}   
                     @{" while      " link "while"}
                     @{" ((...))    " link "((...))"}
@endnode

@node "if" "(if <expression> <true-statement> <false-statement>)"

(if <expression> <true-statement> <false-statement>)

Operates as a standard "if-then" statement.

@endnode

@node "while" "(while <expression> <statement> ... )"

(while <expression> <statement> ... )

Operates as a standard "do-while" statement.

@endnode

@node "until" "(until <expression> <statement> ... )"

(until <expression> <statement> ... )

Operates as a standard "do-until" statement.

@endnode

@node "foreach" "(foreach <drawer name> <pattern> <statement>)"

(foreach <drawer name> <pattern> <statement>)

For each file or directory matching the pattern located in the given drawer
statement will be executed.  The special variables "@{" @each-name " link "each"}" and
"@{" @each-type " link "each"}" will contain the filename and the DOS object type, respectively.
(By DOS object type we mean the same value as found in fib_DirEntryType if
one were to "Examine" the object.) Patterns specified in a script must be no
longer than 64 characters.

@endnode

@node "((...))" "((...) (...) (...))"

((...) (...) (...))

Execute a sequence of statements.  The statements in the parentheses will be
executed in order -- not needed at topmost level.

@endnode

@node "trap" "(trap <trapflags> <statements>)"

(trap <trapflags> <statements>)

Used for catching errors. Works much like C "longjmp", i.e.  when an error
occurs, control is passed to the statement after "trap".  "Trapflags"
determine which errors are trapped.  The trap statement itself returns the
error type or zero if no error occurred.  The current error type values are:

    1 - user aborted
    2 - ran out of memory
    3 - error in script
    4 - DOS error (see @{" @ioerr " link "ioerr"})
    5 - bad parameter data

@endnode

@node "onerror" "(onerror <statements>)"

(onerror <statements>)

When a fatal error occurs that was not trapped, a set of statements can be
called to clean-up after the script.  These statements are logged in by using
the onerror construct.  Note that onerror can be used multiple times to allow
context sensitive termination.

@endnode

@node "select" "(select <n> <item1> <item2> ...)"

(select <n> <item1> <item2> ...)

Only the selected element will be evaluated.  In this manner, "select" can be
used as a case select construct.

@endnode

@node "Debugging Statements" "4.4 Debugging Statements"
   4.4  Debugging Statements

      @{" debug      " link "debug"}
      @{" user       " link "user"}
@endnode

@node "user" "(user <user-level>)"         

(user <user-level>)

Used to change the user level of the current installation.  This statement
should ONLY be used when debugging scripts. Remove such statements from any
script before distribution of your product.  Returns the current @{" user level " link "user-level"}.

@endnode

@node "debug" "(debug <anything> <anything> ...)"

(debug <anything> <anything> ...)

When the Installer is run from a CLI, "debug" will print the values of the
parameters with a space between each parameter.  For example, the statements

    (@{" set " link "set"} myvar 2)
    (debug "This value of 'myvar' is" myvar)

will print "This value of myvar is 2".  If the parameter is an uninitialized
variable, then debug will print "<NIL>" as its value.

@endnode

@node "User-Defined Procedures" "4.5 User-Defined Procedures"
   4.5  User-Defined Procedures

The Installer has user-defined procedures (subroutines).  This functionality
is currently very primitive. There are no local variables. To define a new
procedure, use the "procedure" command:

   (procedure <procedure-name> <statement>)

You can then call the procedure like so:

   (<procedure-name>)

Note that <procedure-name> is not a string, just a symbolic name.

@endnode

@node "Functions" "4.6  Functions"
   4.6  Functions

   @{" +             " link "+"}     @{" BITNOT        " link "baoxn"}     @{" NOT           " link "aoxn"}
   @{" -             " link "-"}     @{" BITXOR        " link "baoxn"}     @{" OR            " link "aoxn"}
   @{" *             " link "*"}     @{" cat           " link "cat"}     @{" pathonly      " link "pathonly"}
   @{" /             " link "div"}     @{" database      " link "database"}     @{" patmatch      " link "patmatch"}
   @{" AND           " link "aoxn"}     @{" earlier       " link "earlier"}     @{" select        " link "select"} 
   @{" askbool       " link "askbool"}     @{" exists        " link "exists"}     @{" shiftleft     " link "shift"}
   @{" askchoice     " link "askchoice"}     @{" fileonly      " link "fileonly"}     @{" shiftrght     " link "shift"}
   @{" askdir        " link "askdir"}     @{" getassign     " link "getassign"}     @{" string        " link "string"}
   @{" askdisk       " link "askdisk"}     @{" getdevice     " link "getdevice"}     @{" strlen        " link "strlen"}
   @{" askfile       " link "askfile"}     @{" getdiskspace  " link "getdiskspace"}     @{" substr        " link "substr"}
   @{" asknumber     " link "asknumber"}     @{" getenv        " link "getenv"}     @{" tackon        " link "tackon"}
   @{" askoptions    " link "askoptions"}     @{" getsize       " link "getsize"}     @{" transcript    " link "transcript"} 
   @{" askstring     " link "askstring"}     @{" getsum        " link "getsum"}     @{" XOR           " link "aoxn"}
   @{" BITAND        " link "baoxn"}     @{" getversion    " link "getversion"}     @{" = > >= < <= <>" link "relational"}
   @{" BITOR         " link "baoxn"}     @{" IN            " link "IN"}

@endnode

@node "string" "(<string> <arguments> ...)"

(<string> <arguments> ...)

The "string substitution function".  Whenever a text string is the first item
in a parenthesized group, the arguments will be substituted into the string
using RawDoFmt.  Note: This function does no argument type checking.

@endnode

@node "cat" "(cat <string> <string> ...)"

(cat <string> <string> ...)

Concatenates the strings and returns the resulting string.

To convert an integer to a string, use the "cat" function.  All integer
arguments to "cat" are converted to strings during concatenation.  Use the
"@{" set " link "set"}" statement to convert a string to an integer.

@endnode

@node "substr" "(substr <string> <start> [<count>])"

(substr <string> <start> [<count>])

Returns a substring of <string>, beginning with the character at offset
<start> (offset begins with 0 for the first character) and including <count>
characters. If <count> is omitted, the rest of the string (to its end) is 
returned.

@endnode

@node "strlen" "(strlen <string>)"

(strlen <string>)

Returns the length of the given string.

@endnode

@node "transcript" "(transcript <string> <string> ...)"

(transcript <string> <string> ...)

Concatenates the strings, appends a newline and then prints the resulting
string to the transcript file (if any).

@endnode

@node "tackon" "(tackon <path> <file>)"

(tackon <path> <file>)

Concatenates the filename to the pathname and returns resulting string.
Currently, "tackon" cannot deal with a leading '/' in the <file> parameter.
This may be fixed in a future version.

@endnode

@node "fileonly" "(fileonly <path>)"

(fileonly <path>)

Returns only the file part of a pathname.

@endnode

@node "pathonly" "(pathonly <path>)"

(pathonly <path>)

Returns only the non-file part of a pathname.

@endnode

@node "expandpath" "(expandpath <path>)"

(expandpath <path>)

Returns the full path, given a shortened path.  For example, it might expand
"SYS:c" to "System2.x:c".

@endnode

@node "askdir" "(askdir <parameters>)"

(askdir <parameters>)

Asks the user for a directory name, with a scrolling list requester.
The user can either create a new directory or specify an existing one.
If the user cancels, the routine will cause an abort.  NOTE: It is always
best to first insure that the volume you want is mounted by using the
"@{" askdisk " link "askdisk"}" command. Parameters:

    @{" prompt  " link "prompt"}  - tell the user what's going to happen.

    @{" help    " link "help"}  - text of help message. 

    @{" default " link "default"}  - default name of directory to be selected.  Note that this may
                 be a relative pathname.

    @{" newpath " link "newpath"}  - allows non-existent paths to be supplied as the default drawer.

    @{" disk    " link "disk"}  - show drive list first.

    @{" assigns " link "assigns"}  - debugging parameter; indicates that logical assigns should
                 satisfy requests as well.  Remove this parameter before
                 distributing disk.

@endnode

@node "askfile" "(askfile <parameters>)"

(askfile <parameters>)

Asks the user for a file name, with a scrolling list requester.  The default
path can be either reference a file or a drawer.  If a file, the filename
gadget is filled in.  Parameters:

    @{" prompt  " link "prompt"}  - tell the user what's going to happen.

    @{" help    " link "help"}  - text of help message. 

    @{" newpath " link "newpath"}  - allows non-existent paths to be supplied as the default drawer.

    @{" disk    " link "disk"}  - show drive list first.

    @{" default " link "default"}  - default name of file to be selected  Note that this may be
                 a relative pathname.

@endnode

@node "askstring" "(askstring <parameters>)"

(askstring <parameters>)

Prompts the user to enter a text string.  Parameters:

    @{" prompt  " link "prompt"}  - tell the user what's going to happen.

    @{" help    " link "help"}  - text of help message. 

    @{" default " link "default"}  - the default text string.

@endnode

@node "asknumber" "(asknumber <parameters>)"

(asknumber <parameters>)

Prompts the user to enter an integer quantity.  Prints the allowed range
below the integer gadget if the "@{" range " link "range"}" parameter is given, and prevents
the user from proceeding without entering a valid number.  Parameters:

    @{" prompt  " link "prompt"}  - tell the user what's going to happen.

    @{" help    " link "help"}  - text of help message. 

    @{" range   " link "range"}  - valid input range of numbers.

    @{" default " link "default"}  - default value

@endnode

@node "askchoice" "(askchoice <parameters>)"

(askchoice <parameters>)

Ask the user to select one out of N choices, using radio buttons.
Parameters:

    @{" prompt  " link "prompt"}  - tell the user what's going to happen.

    @{" help    " link "help"}  - text of help message. 

    @{" choices " link "choices"}  - a list of choice strings, such as "ok" "cancel", etc.

    @{" default " link "default"}  - the number of the default choice (defaults to 0)

@endnode

@node "askoptions" "(askoptions <parameters>)"

(askoptions <parameters>)

Ask the user to select any number of N choices, using checkbox buttons.
A bit mask is returned as a result, with the first bit indicating the state
of the first choice, etc.  Parameters:

    @{" prompt  " link "prompt"}  - tell the user what's going to happen.

    @{" help    " link "help"}  - text of help message. 

    @{" choices " link "choices"}  - a list of choice strings, such as "ok" "cancel", etc.

    @{" default " link "default"}  - a bit mask of the buttons to be checked (defaults to -1)

@endnode

@node "askbool" "(askbool <parameters>)"

(askbool <parameters>)

Ask the user to select yes or no.  Parameters:

    @{" prompt  " link "prompt"}  - tell the user what's going to happen.

    @{" help    " link "help"}  - text of help message. 

    @{" default " link "default"}  - 0 = no, 1 = yes

    @{" choices " link "choices"}  - change the positive and negative text.  The defaults are
                 "Yes" and "No".  So to change the text to "Proceed" and 
                 "Cancel" you would use: (choices "Proceed" "Cancel")

@endnode

@node "askdisk" "(askdisk <parameters>)"

(askdisk <parameters>)

Ask the user to insert a disk in a user friendly manner.  For instance, the
prompt can describe the disk by its label; e.g. "FooBar Program Disk".
This function will not exit until the correct disk is inserted, or the user
aborts.

    @{" prompt  " link "prompt"}  - tell the user what's going to happen.

    @{" help    " link "help"}  - text of help message. 

    @{" dest    " link "dest"}  - the volume name of the disk to be inserted

    @{" newname " link "newname"}  - a name to assign to the disk for future reference.
                 This assignment is done even in Dry Run mode -- it is 
                 considered "safe".
   
    @{" disk    " link "disk"}  - switch to get a drive list to be shown initially.

    @{" assigns " link "assigns"}  - Debugging option; this indicates that logical assigns should
                 satisfy the request as well.  Remove this parameter before
                 distributing disk.

   Note: volume name must be supplied without a colon; i.e. "ENV" not "ENV:".

@endnode

@node "exists" "(exists <filename> (noreq))"

(exists <filename> (noreq))

Returns 0 if does not exists, 1 if a file, and 2 if a directory.  If noreq is
specified, no requester is displayed if the path given is not on a mounted
volume.  In this case the result is 0.

@endnode

@node "earlier" "(earlier <file-1> <file-2>)"

(earlier <file-1> <file-2>)

Returns TRUE if file-1 is earlier than file-2.

@endnode

@node "getsize" "(getsize <filename>)"

(getsize <filename>)

Returns the size of a file.

@endnode

@node "getdevice" "(getdevice <path>)"

(getdevice <path>)

returns the name of the device upon which <path> resides. For example,
"c:mount" as a path might return "WB_2.x".

@endnode

@node "getdiskspace" "(getdiskspace <pathname>)"

(getdiskspace <pathname>)

Returns the available space in bytes on the disk given by pathname.
Returns -1 if the pathname is bad or information could not be obtained from
the filesystem (even though pathname was valid).

@endnode

@node "getsum" (getsum <filename>)"

(getsum <filename>)

Returns the checksum of a file, for comparing versions.

@endnode

@node "getversion" "(getversion <filename> (resident))"

(getversion <filename> (resident))

If the named file has a RomTag with an ID string or a 2.x version string,
this will return the version number.  If filename is not provided, then the
version of the OS is returned instead.  Note that this function does NOT
assume files ending with ".library" or ".device" reside in a particular
place -- the path must be included. If "resident" is specified, attempts to
return version of library or device in memory.  For example:

    (getversion "intuition.library" (resident))

would return the version/revision of intuition.  Note that using the 
"resident" parameter causes first the library and then the device list to be
checked.

The version number is returned as a 32 bit value, where the high order 16 bit
word is the version and the low order word is the revision.  Here is some
sample statements to parse a version number:

(@{" set " link "set"} vernum (getversion "c:iconx"))
(set ver (/ vernum 65536))
(set rev (- vernum (* ver 65536) ) )

(@{" message " link "message"}
        ("You have version " @{" 1.0 " link "Data types" 8}" ver rev)
)

@endnode

@node "getenv" "(getenv <name>)"

(getenv <name>)

Returns the contents of the given ENV: variable.

@endnode

@node "getassign" "(getassign <name> <opts>)"

(getassign <name> <opts>)

Returns the pathname of the object 'name'.  The default is for logical
assignments only, but can be changed using an options string where the
characters are:

    'v' - only match volumes
    'a' - only match logical assignments
    'd' - only match devices

Therefore 'a' would be equivalent to having no options.  Returns an empty
string on failure.

Notes: Name must be supplied without a colon; i.e. "ENV" not "ENV:".
       A variable previously set to name may be used in place of name.
       If a device name is used as the name and the search is limited to
       devices, then "getassign" will return the device or volume name if
       the device exists, otherwise it will return an empty string. 
       An example usage would be (getassign "df1" "d").

@endnode

@node "database" "(database <feature>)"

(database <feature>)

Returns information about the Amiga that the Installer is running on.
"Feature" is a string. This function always returns a string result, 
even if the result looks like a number. If the feature requested is not
recognized, the function returns "unknown".  The currently understood 
features and their possible values are:

    "vblank"         : "50", "60"

    "cpu"            : "68000", "68010", "68020", "68030", "68040"

    "graphics-mem"   : [returns a string representing the amount of free
                       graphics memory]

    "total-mem"      : [returns a string representing the total amount of
                       free memory]

@endnode

@node "select" "(select <n> <item1> <item2> ...)"

(select <n> <item1> <item2> ...)

Returns the value of the Nth item.

@endnode

@node "patmatch" "(patmatch <pattern> <string>)"

(patmatch <pattern> <string>)

Determines if a string matches an AmigaDOS pattern.  Returns either TRUE or
FALSE.

@endnode

@node "relational" "(=  >  >=  <  <=  <>    <expression-1> <expression-2>)"

(=  <expression-1> <expression-2>)
(>  <expression-1> <expression-2>)
(>= <expression-1> <expression-2>)
(<  <expression-1> <expression-2>)
(<= <expression-1> <expression-2>)
(<> <expression-1> <expression-2>)

These are the standard relational expressions.

@endnode

@node "+" "(+  <expression> ...)"

(+  <expression> ...)

Returns the sum of all the arguments.

@endnode

@node "-" "(-  <expression-1> <expression-2>)"

(-  <expression-1> <expression-2>)

Returns the first argument minus the second argument.

@endnode

@node "*" "(* <expression> ...)"

(* <expression> ...)

Returns the product of all the arguments.

@endnode

@node "div" "(/  <expression-1> <expression-2>)"

(/  <expression-1> <expression-2>)

Returns the first argument divided by the second argument.

@endnode

@node "aoxn" "(AND, OR, XOR  <expression-1> <expression-2>), (NOT <expression>)"  

(AND <expression-1> <expression-2>)
(OR  <expression-1> <expression-2>)
(XOR <expression-1> <expression-2>)
(NOT <expression>)

Standard logical functions.

@endnode

@node "baoxn" "(BITAND, BITOR, BITXOR <expression-1> <expression-2>), (BITNOT <expression>)"

(BITAND <expression-1> <expression-2>)
(BITOR  <expression-1> <expression-2>)
(BITXOR <expression-1> <expression-2>)
(BITNOT <expression>)

Bitwise versions of the standard logical functions.

@endnode

@node "shift" "(shiftleft, shiftrght <number> <amount to shift>)

(shiftleft <number> <amount to shift>)
(shiftrght <number> <amount to shift>)

These functions perform a bit-oriented shift by the amount specified.
Zeros are shifted in on the opposite side.

@endnode

@node "IN" "(IN  <expression> <bit number-1> ...)"

(IN  <expression> <bit number-1> ...)

Returns 0 if none of the given bit numbers (starting at 0 for the LSB) is set
in the result of expression, else returns a mask of the bits that were set.

@endnode

@node "Summary of Parameters" "4.7  Summary of Parameters"
   4.7  Summary of Parameters

      @{" all            " link "all"}     @{" newname        " link "newname"}
      @{" append         " link "append"}     @{" newpath        " link "newpath"}
      @{" assigns        " link "assigns"}     @{" nogauge        " link "nogauge"}
      @{" choices        " link "choices"}     @{" noposition     " link "noposition"}
      @{" command        " link "command"}     @{" optional       " link "optional"}
      @{" confirm        " link "confirm"}     @{" pattern        " link "pattern"}
      @{" default        " link "default"}     @{" prompt         " link "prompt"}
      @{" delopts        " link "delopts"}     @{" range          " link "range"}
      @{" dest           " link "dest"}     @{" safe           " link "safe"}
      @{" disk           " link "disk"}     @{" setdefaulttool " link "setdefaulttool"}
      @{" files          " link "files"}     @{" setstack       " link "setstack"}
      @{" fonts          " link "fonts"}     @{" settooltype    " link "settooltype"}
      @{" help           " link "help"}     @{" source         " link "source"}    
      @{" include        " link "include"}     @{" swapcolors     " link "swapcolors"}     
      @{" infos          " link "infos"}     

@endnode

@node "assigns" "(assigns)"                  

(assigns)

A debug option used in the "@{" askdisk " link "askdisk"}" statement to indicate that logical
assigns will match the askdisk request as well. This parameter should not
be used for final disks, only for debugging.

@endnode

@node "help" "(help <string-1> <string-2> ...)"

(help <string-1> <string-2> ...)

This is used to specify the help text for each action.

@endnode

@node "prompt" "(prompt <string-1> <string-2> ...)"

(prompt <string-1> <string-2> ...)

This is used to provide the "title" of the screen which explains to the user
what this step does.

@endnode

@node "safe" "(safe)"

(safe)

This tells the installer that an action not normally performed
in @{" PRETEND mode " link "Pretend mode"} should be performed.

@endnode

@node "choices" "(choices <string-1> <string-2> ...)"

(choices <string-1> <string-2> ...)

Used to display a series of checkmarks.  This is used in the "@{" askchoice " link "askchoice"}"
function to indicate what choices the user has.  It can also be used in the
"@{" copyfiles " link "copyfiles"}" statement to specify that only certain files can be copied. (If
absent, some other criterion will be used to determine which files to copy).

@endnode

@node "pattern" "(pattern <string>)"

(pattern <string>)

Used in the "@{" copyfiles " link "copyfiles"}" statement to specify a wildcard pattern.

@endnode

@node "all" "(all)"

(all)

In the "@{" copyfiles " link "copyfiles"}" statement, specifies that all files are to be copied.

@endnode

@node "source" "(source <filename>)"

(source <filename>)

Specifies the file or directory to be read as part of this command.

@endnode

@node "dest" "(dest <filename>)"

(dest <filename>)

Specifies the file or directory to be modified as part of the command.

@endnode

@node "newname" "(newname <name>)"

(newname <name>)

Used in "@{" copyfiles " link "copyfiles"}" to specify that a file will have a new name after being
copied.  

Used in "@{" askdisk " link "askdisk"}" to assign the new name to the inserted disk.

Used in "@{" copylib " link "copylib"}" to specify that the library will have a new name after
being copied.

@endnode

@node "newpath" "(newpath)"

(newpath)

Used by "@{" askdir " link "askdir"}" and "@{" askfile " link "askfile"}" to allows non-existent paths to be supplied
as the default drawer.

@endnode

@node "confirm" "(confirm <user-level>)"

(confirm <user-level>)

On some statements, the user will only be informed of the action (and 
allowed to cancel it) if the "confirm" option is specified. The @{" user level " link "user-level"}
can be "expert" or "average" ("expert" is the default).

@endnode

@node "files" "files"

(files)

Only copy files. By default the installer will match and copy subdirectories.

@endnode

@node "infos" "(infos)"

(infos)

Indicates to the "@{" copyfiles " link "copyfiles"}" statement that accompanying ".info" files are
to be copied as well. If the destination drawer does not exist, a default
icon will be made for the drawer the Installer creates.

@endnode

@node "fonts" "(fonts)"

(fonts)

Indicates to the "@{" copyfiles " link "copyfiles"}" statement that accompanying ".font" files are
to be copied as well.

@endnode

@node "optional" "(optional <option> <option> ...)"

(optional <option> <option> ...)

Indicates to the "@{" copyfiles " link "copyfiles"}" and "@{" copylib " link "copylib"}" statements that it is not a fatal
error to have a copy fail.  Used for "@{" delete " link "delete"}" to indicate if deletion should
be "forced".

@endnode

@node "delopts" "(delopts <option> <option> ...)"

(delopts <option> <option> ...)

Indicates to the "@{" copyfiles " link "copyfiles"}", "@{" copylib " link "copylib"}" and "@{" delete " link "delete"}" statements that the
listed options should be _removed_ from the global internal list of options
for this statement.  The default global option is "fail".

@endnode

@node "nogauge" "(nogauge)"

(nogauge)

When used with the "@{" copyfiles " link "copyfiles"}" and "@{" copylib " link "copylib"}" statements this disables the
copy status indicator.

@endnode

@node "settooltype" "(settooltype <tooltype> <value>)"

(settooltype <tooltype> <value>)

Used to modify a tooltype to a certain value. If the tooltype does not exist
it will be created; if the <values> parameter is omitted, the tooltype will
be deleted.  A tooltype without a value may be added in the following manner:

    (settooltype <tooltype-string> "")

Remember that (tooltype <tooltype-string>) deletes the tooltype given.

@endnode 

@node "setdefaulttool" "(setdefaulttool <value>)"

(setdefaulttool <value>)

Used to modify the default tool of an icon.

@endnode

@node "setstack" "(setstack <value>)"

(setstack <value>)

Used to modify the stack size included in an icon.

@endnode

@node "noposition" "(noposition)"

(noposition)

Used to modify the positioning of an icon to NO_ICON_POSITION.

@endnode

@node "swapcolors" "(swapcolors)"

(swapcolors)

Used to swap the first two planes of the image of the icon being modified if
the version of the OS if less than 36 (i.e., prior to version 2.0).  This 
does mean that your icons need to have the 2.0 color scheme on your
distribution disks.

@endnode

@node "disk" "(disk)"

(disk)

When used with the "@{" rename " link "rename"}" statement, specifies that a disk relabel
operation is really desired.  When used with the "@{" askdir " link "askdir"}" or "@{" askfile " link "askfile"}"
statement, specifies that a drive list should be shown initially (instead
of a file list).

@endnode

@node "append" "(append <string>)"

(append <string>)

Within a "@{" textfile " link "textfile"}" statement, will append the string to the textfile.

@endnode

@node "include" "(include <filename>)"

(include <filename>)

Within a "@{" textfile " link "textfile"}" statement, will append the listed file to the textfile.

@endnode

@node "default" "(default <value>)"

(default <value>)

Specifies the default value of an @{" askchoice " link "askchoice"}, @{" askstring " link "askstring"}, or @{" asknumber " link "asknumber"} action.

@endnode

@node "range" "(range <min> <max>)"

(range <min> <max>)

Specifies the range of allowable numbers for an @{" asknumber " link "asknumber"} statement.

@endnode

@node "command" "(command <text> ...)"

(command <text> ...)

Specifies the text of a command to be inserted into the S:User-Startup file.
(Argument strings are merged.)

@endnode

@node "Pre-Defined Variables" "4.9 Pre-Defined Variables"
4.9  Pre-Defined Variables

Pre-defined variables are available for use by the install script.  They may
be modified on-the-fly, but their type may not be changed (e.g. from strings
to numeric) unless it never had a value to begin with.

                     @{" @abort-button    " link "abort-button"}
                     @{" @app-name        " link "app-name"}
                     @{" @default-dest    " link "default-dest"}
                     @{" @each-name       " link "each"}
                     @{" @each-type       " link "each"}   
                     @{" @error-msg       " link "error-msg"}
                     @{" @execute-dir     " link "execute-dir"}
                     @{" @icon            " link "icon"}
                     @{" @ioerr           " link "ioerr"}
                     @{" @language        " link "language"}
                     @{" @pretend         " link "pretend_var"}
                     @{" @special-msg     " link "special-msg"}   
                     @{" @user-level      " link "user-level"}
                     @{" @*-help          " link "*-help"}
@endnode

@node "abort-button" "@abort-button"         

   @abort-button

   Replacement text for the "Abort Install" button.

@endnode

@node "app-name" "@app-name"

   @app-name

   The @{" APPNAME " link "APPNAME"} value given as tooltype or CLI option at startup.

@endnode

@node "icon" "@icon"

   @icon

   The pathname of the icon used to start the installer.

@endnode

@node "execute-dir" "@execute-dir"

   @execute-dir

   If this variable is set to a valid path, then the installer will change
directory to it whenever a "@{" run " link "run"}" or "@{" execute " link "execute"}" statement is performed.

@endnode

@node "default-dest" "@default-dest"

   @default-dest

   The installer's suggested location for installing an application.  If you
installed the application somewhere else (as the result of asking the user)
then you should modify this value -- this will allow the "final" statement
to work properly.  Note that creating a drawer and putting the application
in that drawer is considered installing the application somewhere else.
Set it to "" if there really is no definite place that the "application"
was installed. The log file will be copied to the drawer indicated
by @default-dest unless it was set to "".

@endnode

@node "language" "@language"

   @language

   Language specified in @{" LANGUAGE " link "LANGUAGE_OPTION"} tooltype or CLI option, default for
   @language is "english". The use of this variable is left up to the
   install script.

@endnode

@node "pretend_var" "@pretend"

   @pretend

   The state of the Pretend flag (1 if @{" Pretend mode " link "Pretend mode"}).

@endnode

@node "Pretend mode" "Pretend Mode"

   Installer can run in 
      
      "Real" mode, (do it), @{" @pretend " link "pretend_var"} is set to 0 
   or      
      "Pretend" mode, (dry run), @{" @pretend " link "pretend_var"} is then set to 1.

@endnode

@node "user-level" "@user-level"

   @user-level

   The user-level the script is being run at: 
      
         0 for novice, 
         1 for average,
         2 for expert.

@endnode

@node "error-msg" "@error-msg"

   @error-msg

   The text that would have been printed for a fatal error, but was 
   overridden by a @{" trap " link "trap"} statement.

@endnode

@node "special-msg" "@special-msg"

   @special-msg

   If a script wants to supply its own text for any fatal error at various
   points in the script, this variable should be set to that text.  The 
   original error text will be appended to the special-msg within 
   parenthesis. Set this variable to "" to clear the special-msg handling.

@endnode

@node "ioerr" "@ioerr"

   @ioerr

   The value of the last DOS error.  Can be used in conjunction with the
   "@{" trap " link "trap"}" statement to learn more about why an error occurred.

@endnode

@node "each" "@each-name, @each-type"

   @each-name
   
   @each-type

   Used in a "@{" foreach " link "foreach"}" loop.

@endnode

@node "*-help" "Default help text for various functions:"

    @askchoice-help      
    @askdir-help
    @askdisk-help    
    @askfile-help
    @asknumber-help
    @askoptions-help    
    @askstring-help
    @copyfiles-help    
    @copylib-help        
    @makedir-help       
    @startup-help

   Default help text for various @{" functions " link "Functions"}.  These can be appended to the
   explanation provided for a particular action or used as is.

@endnode

@node "Installer Language Quick Reference" "Section 5: Installer Language Quick Reference"
   Section 5: Installer Language Quick Reference

              5.1  @{" Overview                       " link "Overview_5"}
              5.2  @{" Quick Language Overview        " link "Quick Language Overview_5"}
              5.3  @{" Pre-Defined Variables          " link "Pre-Defined Variables_5"}
              5.4  @{" Default Help String Variables  " link "*-help"}
              5.5  @{" Statements                     " link "Statements_5"}
              5.6  @{" Functions                      " link "Functions_5"}

@endnode

@node "Overview_5" "5.1  Overview"
   5.1  Overview

   Attempts to install in "work:" by default if it exists.

   HELP key brings up context-sensitive help.

   Esc key brings up the abort requester.

   Can add assigns to s:User-Startup, and adds lines to s:Startup-Sequence
   (if necessary) to make sure s:User-Startup is executed upon boot-up.

   Can @{" check versions " link "getversion"} of files/libraries.

   Installer can run in @{" 'Real' (do it) or 'Pretend' (dry run) modes " link "Pretend mode"}.

@endnode

@node "Quick Language Overview_5" "5.2  Quick Language Overview"
   5.2  Quick Language Overview

   Language is lisp-like (lots of parentheses (()) (-:).
    
   @{" Variables " link "Data types"} are typeless (a la ARexx), i.e., strings and numbers are
   treated interchangeably.
    
   Strings are delimited with " or '.
    
   Certain @{" embedded sequences " link "Escape Characters"} are available for strings:
        '\\n'    newline        '\\r'    return
        '\\t'    tab            '\\0'    NULL
        '\\"'    double-quote   '\\\\'    backslash
    
   @{" Statements " link "Statements_4"} go in parentheses ( ).  The general format is:
       (operator <operand1> <operand2> ...)
   E.g., to assign the value '5' to the variable 'x', use
       (@{" set " link "set"} x 5)
   To produce the sum of two numbers, use
       (+ 5 9)
   Note that there is no difference between operators and @{" functions " link "Functions"} 
   -- the function '@{" set " link "set"}' and the arithmetic operator '@{" + " link "+"}' are both used exactly
      the same way.
    
   Combining statements: A statement can be used as the operand to another
   statement.  E.g.:
         (set x (+ 3 5))
      In this case, the statement '(+ 3 5)' is evaluated first, and the
      result is 8.  You can think of this as having the '(+ 3 5)' part being
      replaced by an 8, leaving:
         (set v 8)
      Note that the '(+ 3 5)' part actually produced a value: "8".  This is
      called the "result" of the statement.  Many @{" statements " link "Statements_4"} return results,
      even some that might surprise you (such as "set" and "@{" if " link "if"}").
    
   Comments are preceded with a semi-colon ";"
    
   Hex numbers are preceded with a $ (e.g. $23).
    
   Binary numbers are preceded with a % (e.g. %0101).
    
   Many @{" statements " link "Statements_4"} return a value which can be used in assignments, tests,
   etc.
    
   Data can be formatted using a string literal with argument placemarkers,
   for example:
      ("I am 1 foot 0 inches tall." 6 3)
      ;Produces a string with 1's replaced with 6 and 3.
      ;Remember that decimal values must be specified as longwords.

@endnode

@node "Pre-Defined Variables_5" "5.3  Pre-Defined Variables"
   5.3  Pre-Defined Variables

    @abort-button  -  Replacement text for the "Abort Install" button.
    @app-name      -  The @{" APPNAME " link "APPNAME"} being given at startup.
   @{" @default-dest " link "default-dest"} -  Directory where install wants to put things by default.
    @each-name     -  used in "@{" foreach " link "foreach"}" loop.
    @each-type     -  used in "@{" foreach " link "foreach"}" loop.
   @{" @error-msg    " link "error-msg"} -  Message that would be displayed if error not trapped (see @{" trap " link "trap"}).
   @{" @execute-dir  " link "execute-dir"} -  If set to a valid path, installer will change directory to
                      it whenever a "@{" run " link "run"}" or "@{" execute " link "execute"}" statement is performed.
    @icon          -  The pathname of the install script icon.
   @{" @ioerr        " link "ioerr"} -  The value of the last DOS error.
   @{" @language     " link "language"} -  Language specified in tooltypes/CLI (default "english").
   @pretend        -  state of "@{" pretend " link "Pretend mode"}" (dry run mode) flag 0-Real, 1-Pretend.
   @{" @special-msg  " link "special-msg"} -  Custom fatal error message.  
   @{" @user-level   " link "user-level"} -  0-Novice, 1-Average, 2-Expert.
   @{" @*-help       " link "*-help"} -  Default help text for various @{" functions " link "functions"}.

@endnode

@node "Statements_5" "5.5  Statements"
   5.5  Statements

Many commands have standard parameters (some optional):
    
   (@{" all " link "all"})                              ; specifies all files are to copied

   (@{" append " link "append"} <string>)                  ; add string to text file 
                                          (for @{" textfile " link "textfile"})

   (@{" choices " link "choices"} <string1> <string2> ...)  ; radio button options

   (@{" command " link "command"} <string1> <string2>...)   ; add to s:user-startup

   (@{" confirm " link "confirm"} <user-level>)             ; confirmation

   (@{" default " link "default"} <value>)                  ; default value, choice, string, etc.

   (@{" dest " link "dest"} <file>)                      ; output to <file>

   (@{" help " link "help"} <string1> <string2> ...)     ; define current help info

   (@{" include " link "include"} <file>)                   ; insert file in @{" textfile " link "textfile"} statement

   (@{" infos " link "infos"})                            ; copy .info files also

   (@{" newname " link "newname"} <name>)                   ; specify new file or disk name

   (@{" noposition " link "noposition"})                       ; make icon "floating"

   (@{" pattern " link "pattern"} <string>)                 ; used w/ "@{" files " link "files"}" for patterns

   (@{" prompt " link "prompt"} <string1> <string2> ...)   ; text to show user

   (@{" range " link "range"} <min> <max>)                ; numeric input (@{" asknumber " link "asknumber"}) range

   (@{" safe " link "safe"})                             ; force installer to perform action
                                          even if in @{" PRETEND mode " link "Pretend mode"}.

   (@{" settooltype " link "settooltype"} <tooltype> <value>)   ; set icon tool type

   (@{" setdefaulttool " link "setdefaulttool"} <value>)           ; set icon's default tool

   (@{" setstack " link "setstack"} <value>)                 ; set icon's stack value

   (@{" source " link "source"} <file>)                    ; read from <file>

   (@{" swapcolors " link "swapcolors"})                       ; swap first two planes of icon's 
                                          image if OS rev less than v36

   (@{" welcome " link "welcome"} <string> <string> ...)    ; Invokes "welcome" display


Note: Custom parameters are shown below in < >, and standard parameters are
show as (param..) where "param" is one of help, prompt, safe, etc.  
See above for details on standard parameters.

(@{" abort " link "abort"} <string1> <string2> ...)           ; abandon installation

(@{" complete " link "complete"} <num>)                          ; display percentage through 
                                              install in titlebar

(@{" copyfiles " link "copyfiles"} (@{" prompt " link "prompt"}..) (@{" help " link "help"}..) (@{" source " link "source"}..) (@{" dest " link "dest"}..) (@{" newname " link "newname"}..) 
   (@{" choices " link "choices"}..) (@{" all " link "all"}) (@{" pattern " link "pattern"}..) (@{" files " link "files"}) (@{" infos " link "infos"}) (@{" confirm " link "confirm"}..) 
   (@{" safe " link "safe"}) (@{" optional " link "optional"} <option> <option> ...) 
   (@{" delopts " link "delopts"} <option> <option> ...) (@{" nogauge " link "nogauge"}))
                                       ; copy files (and subdir's by default).
                                         (@{" files " link "files"}) option say NO subdirectories.

(@{" copylib " link "copylib"} (@{" prompt " link "prompt"}..) (@{" help " link "help"}..) (@{" source " link "source"}..) (@{" dest " link "dest"}..) (@{" newname " link "newname"}..) 
   (@{" infos " link "infos"}) (@{" confirm " link "confirm"}) (@{ "safe " link "safe"}) (@{" optional " link "optional"} <option> <option> ...) 
   (@{" delopts " link "delopts"} <option> <option> ...) (@{" nogauge " link "nogauge"}))
                                       ; install a library if newer version

(@{" delete " link "delete"} file (@{" help " link "help"}..) (@{" prompt " link "prompt"}..) (@{" confirm " link "confirm"}..) 
   (@{" optional " link "optional"} <option> <option> ...) (@{" delopts " link "delopts"} <option> <option> ...) 
   (@{" safe " link "safe"}))
                                       ; delete file

(@{" execute " link "execute"} <arg> (@{" help " link "help"}..) (@{" prompt " link "prompt"}..) (@{" confirm " link "confirm"}) (@{" safe " link "safe"}))
                                       ; execute script file

(@{" exit " link "exit"} <string> <string> ... (quiet)) ; end installation after displaying 
                                         strings (if provided)

(@{" foreach " link "foreach"} <dir> <@{" pattern " link "pattern"}> <@{" statements " link "Statements_4"}>); do for entries in directory

(@{" if " link "if"} expr truestatements falsestatements)  ; conditional

(@{" makeassign " link "makeassign"} <assign> <path> (@{" safe " link "safe"}))     ; note: <assign> doesn't need `:'
                                            ; create an assignment

(@{" makedir " link "makedir"} <name> (@{" prompt " link "prompt"}..) (@{" help " link "help"}..) (@{" infos " link "infos"}) (@{" confirm " link "confirm"}..) (@{" safe " link "safe"}))
                                            ; make a directory

(@{" message " link "message"} <string1> <string2>...)          ; display message with Proceed, 
                                            Abort buttons

(@{" onerror " link "onerror"} (<@{" statements " link "Statements_4"}>))                ; general error trap

(@{" protect " link "protect"} <file> [<string of flags to change>] [<decimal mask>] <parameters>)
                                            ; Get/Set file protection flags

(@{" rename " link "rename"} <old> <new> (@{" help " link "help"}..) (@{" prompt " link "prompt"}..) (@{" confirm " link "confirm"}..) (@{" safe " link "safe"}))
                                            ; rename files

(@{" rexx " link "rexx"} <arg> (help..) (@{" prompt " link "prompt"}..) (@{" confirm " link "confirm"}..) (@{" safe " link "safe"}))
                                            ; execute ARexx script

(@{" run " link "run"} <arg> (help..) (@{" prompt " link "prompt"}..) (@{" confirm " link "confirm"}..) (@{" safe " link "safe"}))
                                            ; execute program

(@{" set " link "set"} <varname> <expression>)              ; assign a value to a variable

(@{" startup " link "startup"} (@{" prompt " link "prompt"}..) (command..))        ; add a command to the boot scripts
                                             (startup-sequence, user-startup)

(@{" textfile " link "textfile"} (@{" prompt " link "prompt"}..) (@{" help " link "help"}..) (@{" dest " link "dest"}..) (@{" append " link "append"}) 
   (@{" include " link "include"}..) (@{" confirm " link "confirm"}..) (@{" safe " link "safe"}))
                                            ; create text file from other text
                                            files and strings

(@{" tooltype " link "tooltype"} (@{" prompt " link "prompt"}..) (@{" help " link "help"}..) (@{" dest " link "dest"}..) (@{" settooltype " link "settooltype"}..) 
   (@{" setstack " link "setstack"}..) (@{" setdefaulttool " link "setdefaulttool"}..) (@{" noposition " link "noposition"}) (@{" confirm " link "confirm"}..) (@{" safe " link "safe"}))
                                            ; modify an icon

(@{" trap " link "trap"} <flags> <@{" statements " link "Statements_4"}>)             ; trap errors.  flags: 1-abort, 
                                              2-nomem, 3-error, 4-dos, 5-badargs

(@{" until " link "until"} <expr> <@{" statements " link "Statements_4"}>)             ; do-until conditional structure 
                                              (test end of loop)

(@{" welcome " link "welcome"} <string> <string> ...)           ; Allow Installation to commence.

(@{" while " link "while"} <expr> <@{" statements " link "Statements_4"}>)             ; do-while conditional structure 
                                              (test top of loop)

(@{" working " link "working"})                                 ; indicate to user that installer
                                              is busy doing things

@endnode

@node "Functions_5" "5.6  Functions"
   5.6  Functions

(@{" = " link "relational"} <expr1> <expr2>)        ; equality test (returns 0 or 1)

(@{" > " link "relational"} <expr1> <expr2>)        ; greater than test (returns 0 or 1)

(@{" >= " link "relational"} <expr1> <expr2>)       ; greater than or equal test (returns 0 or 1)

(@{" < " link "relational"} <expr1> <expr2>)        ; less than test (returns 0 or 1)

(@{" <= " link "relational"} <expr1> <expr2>)       ; less than or equal test

(@{" + " link "+"} <expr1> <expr2> ...)    ; returns sum of expressions

(@{" - " link "-"} <expr1> <expr2>)        ; returns <expr1> minus <expr2>

(@{" * " link "*"} <expr1> <expr2> ...)    ; returns product of expressions

(@{" / " link "div"} <expr1> <expr2>)        ; returns <expr1> divided by <expr2>

(@{" AND " link "aoxn"} <expr1> <expr2>)      ; returns logical AND of <expr1> and <expr2>

(@{" OR " link "aoxn"} <expr1> <expr2>)       ; returns logical OR of <expr1> and <expr2>

(@{" XOR " link "aoxn"} <expr1> <expr2>)      ; returns logical XOR of <expr1> and <expr2>

(@{" NOT " link "aoxn"} <expr>)               ; returns logical NOT of <expr>

(@{" BITAND " link "baoxn"} <expr1> <expr2>)   ; returns bitwise AND of <expr1> and <expr2>

(@{" BITOR " link "baoxn"} <expr1> <expr2>)    ; returns bitwise OR of <expr1> and <expr2>

(@{" BITXOR " link "baoxn"} <expr1> <expr2>)   ; returns bitwise XOR of <expr1> and <expr2>

(@{" BITNOT " link "baoxn"} <expr>)            ; returns bitwise NOT of <expr>

(@{" shiftleft " link "shift"} <number> <amount to shift>) ; logical shift left

(@{" shiftrght " link "shift"} <number> <amount to shift>) ; logical shift right

(@{" IN " link "IN"} <expr> <bit-number> <bitnumber>...); returns <expr> AND bits

(<@{" format string " link "Data types" 9}> <arg1> <arg2> ...)    ; printf clone

(@{" askdir " link "askdir"} (@{" prompt " link "prompt"}..) (@{" help " link "help"}..) (@{" default " link "default"}..) (@{" newpath " link "newpath"}) (@{" disk " link "disk"})) 
                                         ; ask for directory name

(@{" askfile " link "askfile"} (@{" prompt " link "prompt"}..) (@{" help " link "help"}..) (@{" default "link "default"}..) (@{" newpath " link "newpath"}) (@{" disk " link "disk"}))
                                         ; ask for file name

(@{" askstring " link "askstring"} (@{" prompt " link "prompt"}..) (@{" help " link "help"}..) (@{" default " link "default"}..)) 
                                         ; ask for a string

(@{" asknumber " link "asknumber"} (@{" prompt "l link "prompt"}..) (@{" help " link "help"}..) (@{" range " link "range"}..) (@{" default " link "default"}..)) 
                                         ; ask for a number

(@{" askchoice " link "askchoice"} (@{" prompt " link "prompt"}..) (@{" choices " link "choices"}..) (@{" default " link "default"}..))          
                                         ; choose 1 options

(@{" askoptions " link "askoptions"} (@{" prompt " link "prompt"} (@{" help " link "help"}..) (@{" choices" link "choices"}..) @{" default " link "default"}..))   
                                         ; choose n options

(@{" askbool " link "askbool"} (@{" prompt " link "prompt"}..) (@{" help " link "help"}..) (@{" default " link "default"}..) (@{" choices " link "choices"}..)) 
                                         ; 0=no, 1=yes

(@{" askdisk " link "askdisk"} (@{" prompt " link "prompt"}..) (@{" help " link "help"}..) (@{" dest " link "dest"}..) (@{" newname " link "newname"}..) (@{" assigns " link "assigns"}))
                                         ; Ask the user to insert a disk
                                         
(@{" cat " link "cat"} <string1> <string2>...)  ; returns concatenation of strings

(@{" exists " link "exists"} <filename> (noreq))   ; 0 if no, 1 if file, 2 if dir

(@{" expandpath " link "expandpath"} <path>)           ; Expands a short path to its full path
                                  equivalent

(@{" earlier " link "earlier"} <file1> <file2>)     ; true if file1 earlier than file2

(@{" fileonly " link "fileonly"} <path>)             ; return file part of path (see pathonly)

(@{" getassign " link "getassign"} <name> <opts>)     ; return value of logical name (no `:')
                                  <opts>: 'v' = volumes, 'a' = logical, 
                                          'd' = devices

(@{" getdevice " link "getdevice"} <path>)            ; returns name of device upon which <path> 
                                  resides

(@{" getdiskspace " link "getdiskspace"} <path>)         ; return available space

(@{" getenv " link "getenv"} <name>)               ; return value of environment variable

(@{" getsize " link "getsize"} <file>)              ; return size

(@{" getsum " link "getsum"} <file>)               ; return checksum of file for comparison 
                                  purposes

(@{" getversion " link "getversion"} <file> (@{" resident " link "getversion" 7})) ; return version/revision of file, 
                                     library, etc.. as 32 bit num

(@{" pathonly " link "pathonly"} <path>)                ; return dir part of path (see fileonly)

(@{" patmatch " link "patmatch"} <pattern> <string>)    ; Does <pattern> match <string> ?
                                     TRUE : FALSE

(@{" select " link "select"} <n> <item1> <item2> ...) ; return n'th item

(@{" strlen " link "strlen"} <string>)                ; string length

(@{" substr " link "substr"} <string> <start> [<count>]) ; returns a substring of <string>

(@{" transcript " link "transcript"} <string1> <string2>)    ; puts concatenated strings in log file

(@{" tackon " link "tackon"} <path> <file>)              ; return properly concatenated 
                                        file to path

@endnode

@node "Adaptation" Adaptation of Installer.doc. to AmigaGuide format"

   Note from Gérard Cornu, the 'Guide adapter' ;-) :
   ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
   The original 'Installer.doc' upon which @{" this Guide " link "Guide version"} is based, is 
   (C) Copyright 1991-93 Commodore-Amiga,Inc.  All Rights Reserved.
   
   I have 'only' adapted it to the AmigaGuide format (as supplied with WB 2.1). 

   I have used 'BadLinks' 1.17 by Roger Nedel, to check for bad links 
   (he didn't find any ;-) and 'AGIndex' 1.04 by Camiel Rouweler, to generate
   the index, which I have 'touched up' by hand.
   
   If you find any bugs like bad links, or any other  mistakes pertaining
   only to the adaptation to the Guide format, don't hesitate to send them
   to @{" me " link "adapter"}. Thanks.
      

   @{" Gérard Cornu " link "adapter"}


   @{" Guide history... " link "history"}
      
@endnode

